ce:section.ce:para:
The high surface area of the s-PANI-NTs/GQDs composite and the electrochemical activity of PANI in the positive potential range make this material useful for applications in charge storage. In Fig. 12
                        , the voltammetric responses of the s-PANI-NTs and s-PANI-NTs/GQDs composites were compared for the same masses of electroactive material deposited at the electrode surface. Two poorly separated polyaniline oxidation steps, Ox1/Red1 and Ox2/Red2, were observed for s-PANI-NTs. A significant increase in the current was recorded for the s-PANI-NTs/GQDs composite. PANI-involved redox processes were also more reversible. The polyaniline first oxidation step was significantly shifted towards less positive potentials. A potential separation between the reduction and oxidation peaks was ca. 110 mV for the first polyaniline oxidation step. The peak current of this process linearly depends on the sweep rate for both s-PANI-NTs and s-PANI-NTs/GQDs (Fig. 13
                        ). Such behavior indicated that the rate of s-PANI-NT electrooxidation was limited by the rate of counterion intercalation to maintain the neutrality of electroactive materials.
